      p.c-Lede.c-Lede--dropcap.
        You may already know how to use #[b MathType] (or #[b Equation Editor]) to put
        equations in Moodle. But if you don&rsquo;t have those programs installed on your personal computer,
        or if you don&rsquo;t feel like switching applications often, this short tutorial is just for you.
        You will learn the basics of entering Math into test questions on Moodle&mdash;by hand!
      p.
        This tutorial will teach you the basics of #[span.M \LaTeX]
        (written #[i LaTeX] and pronounced #[i LAH-tech]), which is sort of like a programming language.
        Learning #[span.M \LaTeX] may take some time, but it will save you much more time in
        the long run. Once you are fluent with it, you&rsquo;ll be able to enter math equations without
        ever having to leave the Moodle page.
      section#intro
        h2.c-HeadWithSub Introduction
        p.c-Subhead._subunderline Your First Equation by Hand
        p.
          To enter a math equation into Moodle, you need to surround the math with double
          dollar signs on each side. For example, to display #[span.M 2x+3=7], you
          would need to type #[code $$2x+3=7$$] anywhere in the text box on
          Moodle. Try it for yourself:
        figure(class="!ta:c")
          img(src="images/moodle-inline.png" alt="A screenshot of a dialog box in Moodle with LaTeX input.")
        p.c-Document__Informative(data-informative="").
          The reason you need to surround the #[span.M \LaTeX] code with
          double dollar signs is that there is a JavaScript program installed on the Moodle server that
          searches for these signs. When it finds #[code $$], it knows to convert
          the code inside into mathematical characters. In fact, the same program is installed on this
          web page you&rsquo;re reading right now. In order for #[span.M \LaTeX] to properly
          typeset, you and your students need to have JavaScript enabled in your browsers.
        p.
          Notice how #[span.M \LaTeX] is #[em space-insensitive]. This
          means you could enter #[code $$2x+3=7$$], or
          #[code $$2x + 3 = 7$$], or any variation, and it would still be
          displayed exactly the same. The spaces aren&rsquo;t counted. To deliberately enter a space, you
          need to put a #[em backslash] (not a forward slash) before the space character. For
          example: #[code $$2\ x$$] is displayed as
          #[sppan.M 2\ x]. The #[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key backslash]] key is right above
          the #[kbd: kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key enter] key on your keyboard.
        p.
          All #[span.M \LaTeX] commands begin with a backslash, and may
          contain arguments, which are contained in curly braces. We&rsquo;ll see some more commands in the
          next sections.
      section#modes
        h2 Equation Modes
        p.
          There are two main modes of showing an equation: Inline Mode and Display Mode.
          Inline Mode displays an equation inline with text, like this: #[span.M 2x+3=7].
          In Display Mode, the equation is displayed on its own line and centered. Sometimes I&rsquo;ll
          use the term #[i Block Mode], since really everything is displayed. You might want to use
          Block Mode to isolate an equation to show that it&rsquo;s important:
          #[span.M.M--B 2x+3=7]
        p.
          In normal typesetting systems that use #[span.M \LaTeX], these
          modes are activated differently, however in Moodle they are both activated the same. This means
          you don&rsquo;t have to memorize any special codes to activate Inline versus Block mode. In order
          to show an equation in Block Mode, you&rsquo;ll have to put the equation on its own line and center
          it yourself (like how you would do in #[b Word]).
        figure(class="!ta:c")
          img(src="images/moodle-block.png" alt="A screenshot of a dialog box in Moodle with LaTeX input.")
      section#placement
        h2 Placement of Symbols
        p This short section covers how to place mathematical symbols in semantic ways.
        section#supsub
          h3 Superscripts and Subscripts
          p.
            To enter a superscript for powers or exponents, simply place the exponent in
            curly braces following a caret symbol:
          dl.o-FlexContainer
            dt: code $$a^{2} + b^{2} = c^{2}$$
            dd: span.M a^{2} + b^{2} = c^{2}
          p.
            To enter a subscript, place the subscript in curly braces following an
            underscore:
          dl.o-FlexContainer
            dt: code $$a_{n} = a_{n-1} + d$$
            dd: span.M a_{n} = a_{n-1} + d
        section#frac
          h3 Fraction Bars
          p.
            This one is a little more complicated. To enter a fraction, you need to start
            with the command #[code \frac] (notice the backslash), and then enter
            the arguments in curly braces. There are two arguments: the numerator and the denominator.
          dl.o-FlexContainer
            dt: code $$\frac{-b}{2a}$$
            dd: span.M \dfrac{-b}{2a}
        section#sqrt
          h3 Square Roots
          p.
            The square root command is almost like the fraction command, but it has one
            argument instead of two. The command is #[code \sqrt], and your
            argument should go in curly braces.
          dl.o-FlexContainer
            dt: code $$\sqrt{2}$$
            dd: span.M \sqrt{2}
        section#delimeters
          h3 Parentheses and other Delimiters
          p.
            Sometimes, you may want to put parentheses and other delimiters (absolute
            value, square brackets, curly braces, #[i(lang="la"): abbr(title="et cetera") etc.])
            around an expression or equation. There are many ways to do this, but we&rsquo;ll just cover the
            basics.
          section#parens
            h4 Parentheses
            p To enter parentheses the easy way, just type them in on your keyboard:
            dl.o-FlexContainer
              dt: code $$f(y) = 2(y^{2}+1)$$
              dd: span.M f(y) = 2(y^{2}+1)
            p.
              The parentheses aren&rsquo;t terrible, but since the #[i: span.M y] hangs down a
              little bit, and we have a superscript, we might want to make our parentheses a little bit
              taller so that they&rsquo;ll fit their contents. To do this, we have to use the commands
              #[code \left] and #[code \right] before each parenthesis:
            dl.o-FlexContainer
              dt: code $$f \left( y \right) = 2 \left( y^{2}+1 \right) $$
              dd: span.M f\left(y\right) = 2\left(y^{2}+1\right)
            p.
              It&rsquo;s a little more typing to do, but it makes all the difference. And you
              will want to use these commands to go from this:
              #[span.M (\dfrac{-b}{2a})^{2}] to this:
              #[span.M \left(\dfrac{-b}{2a}\right)^{2}].
          section#brackets
            h4 Absolute Value, Square Brackets
            p.
              Other delimiting symbols work just the same way. You can enter them in on
              your keyboard directly, or you can precede them with the #[code \left]
              and #[code \right] commands.
            p.
              For the absolute value symbol, use the #[kbd: kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key bar] key above
              the #[kbd: kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key enter] key on your keyboard. (It&rsquo;s
              #[kbd #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key shift] + #[kbd.o-Textbox.c-Key backslash]].)
            dl.o-FlexContainer.
              #[dt.u-w_p2c: code $$ |x+2|^{2}+3 $$]               #[dd.u-w_p2: span.M |x+2|^{2}+3]
              #[dt.u-w_p2c: code $$ \left|x+2\right|^{2}+3 $$]    #[dd.u-w_p2: span.M \left|x+2\right|^{2}+3]
              #[dt.u-w_p2c: code $$ [x^{2}+6x+9]-9 $$]            #[dd.u-w_p2: span.M [x^{2}+6x+9]-9]
              #[dt.u-w_p2c: code $$ \left[x^{2}+6x+9\right]-9 $$] #[dd.u-w_p2: span.M \left[x^{2}+6x+9\right]-9]
          section#braces
            h4 Curly Braces
            p.
              Now, curly braces are a different situation. Since the
              #[span.M \LaTeX] language uses these symbols for its command arguments,
              we can&rsquo;t just type them in like we would normal parentheses. We have to #[em escape]
              them with a backslash. To get #[span.M \{4,2,1,\dfrac{1}{2},\dots\}],
              for example, we would have to type
              #[code $$ \{ 4,2,1,\frac{1}{2},\dots \} $$]. Notice the backslash before each brace.
            p.
              Again, if we want to stretch the braces to fit their contents, we have to
              add the #[code \left] and #[code \right] commands:
            dl.o-FlexContainer
              dt: code $$ \left\{ 4,2,1,\frac{1}{2},\dots \right\} $$
              dd: span.M \left\{4,2,1,\dfrac{1}{2},\dots\right\}
